Introduction

The purpose of this project is to predict the sale prices of homes in Boston given other, known characteristics about the house. Creating models which can predict home prices is both a public and private sector concern – it helps real estate investors figure out where new markets may be taking off, and allows city governments to target properties which may need a tax reassessment. This is a difficult exercise because there are myriad factors, both internatl and external, which determine how much a buyer pays for a house. A house also may be attractive to a certain income group and unnatrractive to others based on unmeasurable or individual characteristics unmeasurable in big data sets.

Our overall strategy was to look at surrounding home sales, the livable area of the house, commute time, and the household size to determine home price. We were able to account for just around 90% of the variance in home prices with our model. We found that more expensive and cheaper homes tendened to cluster together, and accounting for these clusters allowed us to better predict home sale prices.

We gathered our data using a combination of American Community Survey Data from 2011 to 2015, already-existing variables provided in the data set, and data-mining techniques. For ACS Data, we assigned properties characteristics of their Census Block.

Methods

Our guiding philosophy is to consider factors that potential home sellers/buyers and property tax officials would consider when assessing home price. We used three variables to represent the factors that the above mentioned parties are mostly likely to take into consideration when assessing the price of a house. These variables are price for nearby houses, transit availability, and living area.

For transit availability, we took information from the American Community Survey about the average commute time from each census block and applied that to homes which fell in those boundaries.

For price for nearby houses, we splitted the training data set into 20 quantiles based on their per sqft sales price. we then assigned a category to houses in each quantile. We then used selecting by location in GIS to find houses in the testing data that are in the vicinity of houses in each category. This allowed us to assign a category number to the testing data based on the per sqft price of the nearest houses in the training data. For those houses (in testing set) that are in the vicinity of multiple categories, we went on Google map to find out which category would be the most sensible. Given how clustered the per sqft sales prices are, there are many reasons to believe that a house (in the testing set) that falls in a sea of, say, Category 5 houses in training set ($200 - $210/sq ft), is also likely to be a category 5. By doing so, we made use of the spatial autocorrelation of housing prices (although houses in the same category may not be all in the same area).

Discussion

This is a relatively effective model because our MAPE was below 10% and we could explain 90% of variation in prices with our model.

This model is effective when predicting non-extreme housing prices. It tends to underestimate extremely low value houses and overestimate extremely high value houses. The reason for this inaccuracy might be because some of the extremely low and high value houses have very few nearby houses that reflect their value. As a result, the category to which these houses were assigned might not be an effective representation of their actual value. There were still spatial variation in prices in our model, but we were able to account for more of this variation through our variables, particularly the ones described below.

The most interesting variables are the ones related to the neighborhood/vicinity and the ones that reflect housing characteristics. In particular, the price category and commute variables, which reflect the neighborhood characteristics, and living area, stood out as the most relevant. Interestingly, we did not find other housing characteristics such as number of floors, bathrooms, total rooms, kitchens to be highly influential. Furthermore, demographic information also were not highly correlated with housing prices (their influence is perhaps already well captured by the neighborhood characteristics variables we have in the model).

Conclusion

We would recommend my model to my boss at Zillow. We would also point out to him/her that the model performs better at predicting housing prices that are neither extremely low nor high. In other words, the model may not be generalizable to very rich and very poor neighborhoods.

There are a few ways we could improve this model. First and foremost, the plot shows that an outlier with extremely high price in the data set compromises the performance of our model. We would refit this model without this outlier. Secondly, when assigning price categories to each property, we only considered the properties in the immediate vicinity of the ones in question. We would broaden our search radius to include more properties and see if it improve the performance of our model. Lastly, there are certain factors that we did not consider, such as presence of bike share station, school district, quality of nearby donut shops, etc. We would examine these variables to refine our model.
